Introduction

This document serves as an EDA for a dataset about red variant of the Portugeuese “Vinho Verde” wine. It contains 1599 observations and 12 variables, out of which 11 are numerical and continuous based on physicochemical tests and 1 (quality) is a discrete numerical variable corrensponding to experts’ assessment.

There are no missing values in the dataset.

Analysis

Distributions

First, we will look at histograms for each variable and see if we notice anything interesting.

No obvious abnormalities. Density of wine is very close to that of water (1.00). It seems that 3 of the variables: density, pH, volatile.acidity follow normal distribution. Let’s check it.

density seems to fit closely to the line, with differences at the beginning and at the end. pH fits very closely to the ideal normal distribution. volatile.acidity seems to be a bit over the q-q line.

Correlation

Correlation matrix proposes interesting relations, which we’ll look into. We’re mostly interested which variables influence quality the most. We won’t look into relations that seem very weak at the first glance.

Influence on the dependent variable

The lower the value of volatile.acidity, the more chance a wine has to be rated higher. This relation works best for lower-medium tier wines. There is one outlier with quality 3, that reinforces numeric evaluation of correlation.

The higher the value of citric.acid, the more chance a wine has to be rated higher. We can see abnormally many observations citric.acid=0.00 and citric.acid=0.90. Even some wines with quality=7 had no citric acid detected.

There seems to be no correlation between the variables on the first glance.

The lower the density, the better the quality. This is probably due to strong relation of both variables with alcohol variable. It’s understandable, as alcohol is less dense than water. density seems to take a wide range of values for medium quality.

The higher the value of sulphates, the higher the quality. It is interesting, that there are no wines with quality=8 and really low values of sulphates, which is the case for wines of lower quality.

The higher the value of alcohol, the higher the quality. This stands true mostly for the higher rated wines. Alcohol seems to not have been rated on a truly continuous scale, because there are visible steps. This is the strongest predictor of the quality of wine. This coincides with my personal observations.

Relations between independent variables

The higher the value of alcohol, the lower the value of density. This is not surprising, as alcohol is less dense than water.

The higher the value of fixed.acidity, the lower the value of pH. It also comes as no surprise. The relation doesn’t look exactly linear, for higher values of pH, it becomes weaker.

The higher the value of citric.acid, the lower the value of pH.

The higher the value of density, the higher the value of fixed.acidity. The relation seems to be approximately linear.

The higher the value of total.sulfur.dioxide, the higher the value of free.sulfur.dioxide. That probably isn’t surprising, but there seems to be greater variance for higher total.sulfur.dioxide values. This looks somewhat like a cone.

The higher the value of fixed.acidity, the higher the value of citric.acid. The relation seems linear, with fairly constant deviation.

The higher the value of volatile.acidity, the lower the value of citric.acid. The relation looks like a mirror to the previous one.

Conclusion

My intuition was right. The more alcohol, the better. We also learned other interesting facts, for example that alcohol is less dense than water.

The dataset is very interesting, it was a surprise to me, that highly rated wines can vary so much in terms of chemical contents. It goes to show, that taste is a very subjective and complex topic. However personal it seems though, there are some interesting relations, that can be helpful to determine whether the quality is good.

Unfortunately, there is not information about chemical contents on labels of wines I buy at the local Biedronka store.
